5000|$|The {{official}} ghetto {{was established}} in Lublin on 24 March 1941. The expelled Jews have been returned there. This measure was driven by {{the need for the}} new proper housing for the arriving German military, which was preparing for Operation Barbarossa. In the Lublin district, another ghetto {{was established in}} Piaski. In October and December 1941, the local administration and the Sicherheitspolizei headquarters issued decrees <b>about</b> <b>the</b> instant <b>death</b> <b>penalty</b> for <b>the</b> Jews caught leaving the Jewish district. Any Christian Pole harbouring Jews on the Aryan side of the city was to be executed along with his family. The ghetto inmates were terrorized by the Waffen-SS battalion of Oskar Dirlewanger, engaging in extortion, murder and rape (Rassenschande) to such an extend that they had to be moved elsewhere, yet again.|$|R
